Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 15/8/1939
Source: NZ Journal of Agriculture
Author:
Vol / Page: 129
Edition:
Quote: .. often plants on the end of the rows look entirely different from the rest of the crop because they have been trodden on by the horses manoeuvring to turn. I have heard such plants described as suffering from "swingle tree blight."
